1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,955
Pandas supports a wide array of data types,

2
00:00:02,955 --> 00:00:06,600
but the difficult types you will encounter include objects.

3
00:00:06,600 --> 00:00:08,655
These are typically strings,

4
00:00:08,655 --> 00:00:12,060
integers, whole numbers like zero, one,

5
00:00:12,060 --> 00:00:15,105
and two, floats,

6
00:00:15,105 --> 00:00:18,255
which are floating point numbers with high precision.

7
00:00:18,255 --> 00:00:22,905
Booleans, you'll see these as true or false.

8
00:00:22,905 --> 00:00:27,675
Datetimes, these include the date and the time into a single value.

9
00:00:27,675 --> 00:00:31,305
Sometimes you'll see these as timestamps.

10
00:00:31,305 --> 00:00:33,720
Finally, categorical.

11
00:00:33,720 --> 00:00:35,970
We'll use these later in the lesson,

12
00:00:35,970 --> 00:00:40,210
but these data types help organize string representations in your DataFrame.

13
00:00:40,210 --> 00:00:42,860
There are many more, and I suggest you look

14
00:00:42,860 --> 00:00:45,665
at the pandas documentation to review them all.

15
00:00:45,665 --> 00:00:47,855
To change a column's datatype,

16
00:00:47,855 --> 00:00:50,135
you can use the astype method.

17
00:00:50,135 --> 00:00:52,790
This works with either a dictionary mapping on

18
00:00:52,790 --> 00:00:57,680
the entire DataFrame or converting the column by accessing the series.

19
00:00:57,680 --> 00:01:02,970
You will still need to assign it back to the DataFrame for the conversion to persist.

